ode[black, below left] at (0,0) { ootnotesize O}; % Points \draw[black, thick] (0,2) ++(-0.15, -0.15) -- ++(0.3, 0.3) ++(-0.3, 0) -- ++(0.3, -0.3); 
ode[black, above right] at (0,2) {E}; \draw[black, thick] (3,0) ++(-0.15, -0.15) -- ++(0.3, 0.3) ++(-0.3, 0) -- ++(0.3, -0.3); 
ode[black, above right] at (3,0) {F}; \draw[black, thick] (0,0) ++(-0.15, -0.15) -- ++(0.3, 0.3) ++(-0.3, 0) -- ++(0.3, -0.3); \draw [line width=1.pt,color=black] (0,2)-- (3,0); \draw [line width=1.pt,color=black] (0,0)-- (3,0); \draw [line width=1.pt,color=black] (0,2)-- (0,0); \end{tikzpicture} Le triangle EOF est un triangle rectangle en O car le repère est orthogonal. Le théorème de Pythagore me permet donc d'écrire: EF^2 &= OE^2 + OF^2 EF^2 &= 2^2 + 3^2 EF^2&= 4 + 9 EF^2&= 13 <strong>La distance exacte est $\mathbf{EF = \sqrt{13}}$.</strong>

